---
title: Safety and open source
description: "Our point of view: flight safety should depend neither on budget nor on a vendor. Visibility equipment must be affordable, and its code open."
---

<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">Our point of view</h2>
  <h3>Safety is not a premium feature.</h3>

  <p>
    The mid-air collision remains one of the most serious accidents in
    general aviation, and one of the most avoidable. The technology to be visible has
    existed for years. Yet it remains rare in cockpits: expensive equipment,
    proprietary systems incompatible with one another, subscriptions.
  </p>

  <h3>Affordable, because equipment left on the shelf protects no one</h3>
  <p>
    Safety equipment only works if it is on board: of every aircraft, not
    just the best equipped. We pick the most affordable radio hardware on the
    market, mass-produced, generally under a hundred euros, far from the
    price of a certified instrument. Once the device is bought, transmitting
    your position and receiving traffic costs nothing: no subscription.
  </p>

  <h3>Open source, because safety equipment should not be a black box</h3>
  <p>
    The code that transmits your position, receives traffic and triggers the
    alarms is public. Anyone can read it, verify it, fix it and improve it.
    And it does not depend on the survival of one company: the firmware and
    its sources will remain available, whatever happens.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="pledge">
  <h2 class="kicker">The commitment</h2>
  <h3>Permanent.</h3>
  <p>
    In skyBlip and skyPost, all safety functions (the ADS-L implementation,
    position transmission, traffic reception, alarms, the ground uplink) are
    published under an open-source licence, free of charge and with no
    subscription. <strong>This commitment is permanent.</strong>
  </p>
</section>

